The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a major shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, indeed, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or “less bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that this is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is still lacking to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume that this is about Higgs, since the chances of getting it wrong seem small. We'll see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because you’ll end up getting hurt.
Although the physics of particles is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories website The Particle Adventure, which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not speak here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, one might point out here, are not the exotic beasts we might believe.
In fact, if he manages to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disorders” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, of infrared, of ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
The most stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, you need to reach extremely high energies, a bit like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide on the surface.
It takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN (the big hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don’t: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick on its own to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what can all these investigations “contribute” to? asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and predictions of MS.
For their part, many want to find each other fervently, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (other ups!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The impact of such research on our day-to-day lives is difficult to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say it won’t have any.
Let’s face it: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories had no idea at all what a revolution their work would bring.
They understood the scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle said, who worked in the Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Just imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this pickup now serves as an "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
