A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, modified several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial turmoil.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his “autocratic delusions” and continues “betraying his word” and “trapping the right.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a measure to put an end to the institutional and political crisis faster and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the polemic wreaks havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either vote my text or keep my powers fully", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
The majority of liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not make their views stand.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As you might expect, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are pleased, on the other hand, that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent Assembly clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on late yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all views, remains finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because “people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of the university would be much less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used mimic the religious vocabulary.
“We are referring specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that could arise in the future would be to what extent are the competent civil judges to rule above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Neither will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider libertarian.
The crime of blasphemy continues and from now on insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially in the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to go out on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
