Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
On December 1, a law came into force that required every immigrant to take an exam to check their knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to pass the examination of the language, if not also that of Russian history and that of the fundamentals of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even in order to receive and renew the work permit.
Exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law shall not apply to persons who obtained their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
