How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it a similar office to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized in another way?
As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to ours, with a school too, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The competences are also to some extent analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of account are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Accounts.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not normally like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it cannot be clarified exactly what is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make this kind of comparison.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model have to face a large number of problems.
If it weren't for that, you wouldn't have any benefit from collaborating with our office, don't you think?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office, and does it have any bearing on its impact?
Given the relatively short period of validity of this amendment, it has not yet manifested itself in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is seen in the process of preparing future checks: we have started a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you consider that the passage of this law is beneficial or rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulation, controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense, then, to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no bearing on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We’ll see where this started path takes us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDGs would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0x9B>varc system, referring to the fact that they are autonomous only on paper.
Is the svarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the Prime Minister of the government can impede the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such checks and demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but you can't say we're going to act like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how formal action should be taken, and this is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we are missing.
