Szabo: "Germans must play a more prominent role"
Germany has abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather troubled diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany indicated that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories the status of an observer state of the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
What's wrong with that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, due to the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American stance either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because at the moment it is reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they’re still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they’ve already started the way to a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries such as France or Great Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful not to alienate itself from the Arab public opinion or the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn’t give it that much importance because it’s not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps this has earned Germany some respect for itself.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the U.S. has clearly shown itself in favour of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of US domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I believe that the true disparity of views does not actually have the scale that is attributed to it.
If we look at the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but must push things from their own position.
That is exactly what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European stance.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship it maintains with Israel.
This has always been a tricky topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they should play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international actor? Does Germany really want to take a leading role?
Or do you find it hard to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet become accustomed, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as the main actor, certain anti-German feelings are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and is that no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
In this way, Germany finds itself in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The U.S. influence in European politics is diminishing more and more, but the EU is not currently covering that gap, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take on a more prominent role.
Even if they don't like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular town, c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it's not clear that they're going to be right.
“Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada registers Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a repository in which it holds seats from Beijing’s trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are department stores of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature; on behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a denomination that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have “fished” a rich man.
Chinese authorities don’t feel guilty
“It’s bad for the business, we have to fight it,” Pattloch says.
“The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage suffered by the image is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are multimillion-dollar, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year, China is, in size, the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the trademark registration is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The process can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had been so long that the name in question had already become a "market reality".
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged his brand in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphical elements.
In 2009, Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely initially used a blue and white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they had difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the labor emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is usual in China, the numbers are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth year in a row, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in rights would have been pocketed.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family company Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese impersonator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
The impersonator has managed to secure Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich appeal.
In the following two instances they have given Freudenberg the right, but the opposite side continues to fight today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler hoped that the matter would be resolved in a favourable manner and commended the professionalism of the courts.
However, it also states that "the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time."
It is difficult to estimate the internal costs; the business file has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "six-figure euro sum" with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten to even affect Europe.
In particular, if imitators secure rights over unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial field, however, it managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend German companies to be extremely prudent when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trade mark law, but what needs to be done is to "record also in China everything that may be susceptible to protection," as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the subject may prove to be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposite party license rights by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
