The Norwegian rakfish: the most stinky fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country’s success has anything to do with its greed for an extremely stinky fish?
Take a series of over-cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of wet and dirty football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the crisp aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway’s delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
The rakfish is salted trout that is allowed to ferment in water for up to a year, depending on how odourful you prefer.
As it gets darker and colder, the Norwegians flock to a festival that is held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this delicacy of the most, so to speak, captivating.
"You eat raw and then you drink a glass of aquavit from a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of Rakfisk", who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small cubes and drinking from a drink significant amounts of the drink.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfish,” says Havard.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I'll try a few pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it’s not bad; it’s not much different from a portion of sushi that you’ve traveled a few kilometers by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty plagued Norway and in which, before cooling existed, fish was stored during the autumn immersed in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is removed and, evidently with the inactive senses due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and even not too much richer than Norway, arrives in this country to work.
The rakfish is considered an important part, an essential but rather odourful part of Norway’s past.
It is among the most expensive dishes that can be bought.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you the 10<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> ($14) frill each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it to be so.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22 event.”
The Norwegians find it very difficult to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway’s current wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“Oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she walks past rakfish trays and that, with her long blonde mane and her amazing blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
