His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; everything, except a small percentage of the money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money that they didn’t have in the years leading up to the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept the wallet tight.
“As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
"And eat rakfish," he adds with a squeaky twist.
I’m in the snow lining up to eat something; I’ve already had enough rakfish.
Now a moose burger is definitely something different and quite succulent to taste.
But at night, that stinking fish comes back.
The hotel I stay at is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A TV has connected live with a presenter who wears a birdie and is surrounded by rakfish dishes.
Looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls from the chair, perhaps beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe they're the vapors of all that fish.
