Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to address allegations of abuse of Bradley Manning during his stay in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The military soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation that the prosecution conducted on Manning in a pre-trial view in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of the weekly visits of unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaint about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence’s request to dismiss the case given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already entailed sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought about committing suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In Friday’s view, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after Manning’s visits during his arrest at the Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers reportedly asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the bailiffs as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities generally as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, despite officers asking Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about those issues and had told him that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
“They were writing ‘no incidents’ (after talking about the issues) but that doesn’t necessarily mean I didn’t mention any issues,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had put him under that restrictive regime, which is a degree below the surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of other people.
“I wanted the senior staff to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a few slingshots, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move around all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the jailers and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given by the janitor that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic bandage on his underwear or flip-flops to injure himself, but that he had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, panties and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
Her lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences she went through during her stay in prison and drastically reduce her sentence in case she was convicted on the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to make Manning guilty of minor crimes and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was detained in accordance with the rules of application to all detainees who are in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally causing the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
