The Tobacco Packaging Act comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases appear on green off-colored boxes, which are the same for all tobacco brands
Australia’s world-leading tobacco and generic packaging law comes into force and replaces logos and brand colors with a wrapper of an olive-green off, scary images of diseased body parts, and depictions of sick children and babies as children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed in a small type of font.
This is the most stringent regime in the world applied to tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government says the goal is to deter young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit have glamour.
It relies on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never do so.
“You can see that children, even from a very early age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies showing, for example, how girls linked the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest rates of smokers in the world and these changes won’t affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies said the law would encourage the black market for tobacco, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more affordable.
“The legislation will bring serious unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia.
Other people say their business has benefited from the passing of the law.
Sandra Ha, of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, claimed that the demand for pickpockets and silicone covers to cover the nasty pictures of the cartridges had skyrocketed almost from zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a lawsuit in court.
Ms. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and that she was expecting more stocks.
“It’s a good business for us.”
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector to which the plan is directed.
After a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most sellers not to put cigarettes in sight, tobacco marketing has gone online.
Australia has banned Internet advertising to local businesses and websites, but cannot restrict it to foreign websites.
“If you market tobacco and you only have this small window to promote your products, online space is the most compelling place to be,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in reviews about brands from “walking citizens” posted on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if this is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble of making a video or if any marketing company is behind it all.
The British American Tobacco of Australia indicated that the industry is more focused on what the new regulations imply than on marketing.
