In a constantly connected world, it’s not so bad to get a little bored
During this year’s Thanksgiving party, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting the duty-free shops.
But there are more and more academics and child development experts praising the goodness of boredom.
According to them, it’s okay that both we and our children get bored from time to time.
Boredom forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in a good way?
Oh, yeah.
And no, I don't.
But, we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press, is not.
“In fact, the story of boredom is very extensive,” he says.
In the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating from the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways,” says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining published research and raising the idea before a 100-person discussion group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able, to engage in an activity that fills you.”
He argues that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boredom can sound awfully similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be their own.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study “The Uningaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to a full-volume television program that had no connection, others listened to it with the low volume, so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group who listened to the program with the volume low showed more boredom than the other two groups; they found it difficult to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, altered attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the study's authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like detecting defective parts on a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not get bored.”
“In fact, we currently know that moving or scratching, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, as they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be quiet,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a “boring tendency scale” in the 1980s.
The scale includes issues such as “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do it all.”
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external stimulation and more varied.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
It found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that “adolescence is a period where boredom reaches its highest levels,” largely because both children and adolescents are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as making bets or falling into substance use as a method of combating it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“ Boredom is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what’s most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to dose himself,” says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dose applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but learns to better control himself in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate it to something worth it,” he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.”
