The World's Toughest Trade: Kawah Ijen's Human Mules
For four euros, carriers of the Indonesian volcano play with life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas that emanates from the bowels of the Earth solidifies by coming into contact with the air.
After ripping out large rocks of sulfur, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two baskets of bamboo that loads on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at the pace of a turtle, keeping the balance and measuring their steps with a zeal not to slip and fall through the cliff.
They know that any traspié could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who got away years ago with the risks of Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters in height.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better, to its workers, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for every kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As usual it is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually performs three daily doors.
It takes three hours on each and ends up ground, but they allow you to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a misery to such inhumane effort, it is three times what you would earn in the field.
"The newspaper of the miners is very high here, where the collection of coffee is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros) ", clarifies the porter, who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the tajo was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as strong as the sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where she is translating to the Hindus, and I have the
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing with his skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pass him the bill despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that the volcano releases.
It’s the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this sympathetic and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy log cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop roaring at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends to the crater, lighting a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 carriers load sulfur baskets onto their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its small profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs or supplies any equipment to carriers, who work on their own and at so much weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that, together with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old self-sufficient carrier who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working “everything he can” because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and peels the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and catches the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... beyond, of course, their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at 53 years old.
Every day, he and his companions pluck 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse of Tamansari, 18 kilometers away by a goat road between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth, where he is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works with sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest trades in the world: the one made by the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
